Volume 3277 of the series Lecture Notes in Computer Science pp 1-16 Parallel Job Scheduling — A Status Report Dror G. Feitelson Affiliated with Lancaster University School of Computer Science and Engineering, The Hebrew University of Jerusalem , Larry Rudolph Affiliated with Carnegie Mellon University Laboratory for Computer Science, Massachusetts Institute of Technology , Uwe Schwiegelshohn Affiliated with Carnegie Mellon University Computer Engineering Institute, Universität Dortmund The popularity of research on the scheduling of parallel jobs demands a periodic review of the status of the field. Indeed, several surveys have been written on this topic in the context of parallel supercomputers [17, 20]. The purpose of the present paper is to update that material, and to extend it to include work concerning clusters and the grid.